name: Contour
description: A line joining points of equal height. The standard vertical interval between contours is 5 m. A contour interval of 2.5 m may be used for flat terrains.

name: Index contour
description: Every fifth contour shall be drawn with a thicker line. This is an aid to the quick assessment of height difference and the overall shape of the terrain surface.

name: Form line
description: Used where more information must be given about the shape of the ground. Form lines are added only where representation would be incomplete with ordinary contours.

name: Earth bank
description: Abrupt change in ground level which can be clearly distinguished from its surroundings, e.g. gravel or sand pits, road and railway cuttings or embankments.

name: Earth wall
description: Distinct earth wall.

name: Ruined earth wall
description: A ruined or less distinct earth wall.

name: Erosion gully
description: An erosion gully which is too small to be shown using symbol Earth bank (104) is shown by a single line.

name: Small erosion gully
description: A small erosion gully, dry ditch or trench.

name: Small knoll
description: An obvious mound or knoll which cannot be drawn to scale with a contour.

name: Small elongated knoll
description: An obvious elongated knoll which cannot be drawn to scale with a contour.

name: Small depression
description: A small depression or hollow without steep sides that is too small to be shown by contours.

name: Pit
description: A pit or hole with distinct steep sides which cannot be shown to scale using symbol Earth bank (104).

name: Broken ground
description: An area of pits and / or knolls which is too intricate to be shown in detail, or other types of rough and uneven ground that is clearly distinguishable but has little impact on runnability.

name: Very broken ground
description: An area of pits and/or knolls, which is too intricate to be shown in detail, or other types of rough and uneven ground that is clearly distinguishable and affects runnability.

name: Prominent landform feature
description: The feature must be very clearly distinguishable from its surroundings.

name: Impassable cliff
description: A cliff, quarry or earth bank that is so high and steep that it is impossible to pass/climb or is dangerous.

name: Cliff
description: A passable cliff or quarry. If the direction of fall of the cliff is not apparent from the contours, or to improve legibility, short tags may be drawn in the direction of the downslope.

name: Rocky pit or cave
description: Rocky pits, holes, caves or mineshafts which may constitute a danger to the competitor.

name: Boulder
description: A distinct boulder (should be higher than 1 m), which is immediately identifiable on the ground. Groups of boulders are represented using symbol Boulder cluster (207) or a boulder field symbol (208, 209).

name: Large boulder
description: A particularly large and distinct boulder. A large boulder should be more than 2 m high.

name: Gigantic boulder or rock pilar
description: A gigantic boulder, rock pillar or massive cliff shall be represented in plan shape. The objects can vary in shape and width.

name: Boulder cluster
description: A distinct group of boulders so closely clustered together that they cannot be marked individually. The boulders in the cluster should be higher than 1 m.

name: Boulder field
description: An area covered with so many scattered blocks of stone that they cannot be marked individually.

name: Dense boulder field
description: An area covered with so many blocks of stone that they cannot be marked individually and the runnability is affected.

name: Stony ground slow running
description: Stony or rocky ground which reduces runnability to about 60-80% of normal speed.

name: Stony ground walk
description: Stony or rocky ground which reduces the runnability significantly (to about 20-60% of normal speed).

name: Stony ground fight
description: Stony or rocky ground which is hardly passable (less than 20% of normal speed).

name: Sandy ground
description: An area of soft sandy ground where runnability is reduced to less than 80% of normal speed.

name: Bare rock
description: A runnable area of rock without earth or vegetation should be shown as bare rock.

name: Trench
description: Rocky or artificial trench. Minimum depth should be 1 m.

name: Uncrossable body of water
description: Uncrossable body of water. The black bank line emphasises that the feature is uncrossable.

name: Shallow body of water
description: Shallow body of water. A shallow seasonal or periodic body of water may be represented using a dashed outline.

name: Waterhole
description: A water-filled pit or an area of water which is too small to be shown to scale.

name: Crossable watercourse
description: A crossable watercourse. Should be at least 2 m wide.

name: Small crossable watercourse
description: A small crossable watercourse.

name: Minor/seasonal water channel
description: A natural or man-made minor water channel which may contain water only intermittently.

name: Uncrossable marsh
description: A marsh which is uncrossable or dangerous for the competitor. The black outline emphasises that the feature is uncrossable.

name: Marsh
description: A crossable marsh, usually with a distinct edge.

name: Narrow marsh
description: A marsh or trickle of water which is too narrow (less than about 5 m wide) to be shown with the marsh symbol.

name: Indistinct marsh
description: An indistinct marsh, seasonal marsh or an area of gradual transition from marsh to firm ground, which is crossable.

name: Well, fountain or water tank
description: A prominent well, fountain, water tank or captive spring.

name: Spring
description: A source of water.

name: Prominent water feature
description: Prominent water feature.

name: Open land
description: Open land that has a ground cover (grass, moss or similar) which offers better runnability than typical open forest.

name: Open land with scattered trees
description: Areas with scattered trees or bushes in open land.

name: Rough open land
description: Heath, moorland, felled areas, newly planted areas (trees lower than 1 m) or other generally open land with rough ground vegetation, heather or tall grass offering the same runnability as typical open forest.

name: Rough open land with scattered trees
description: Areas with scattered trees or bushes in rough open land.

name: Forest
description: Typical open forest for the particular type of terrain. If no part of the forest is easily runnable then no white should appear on the map.

name: Vegetation: slow running
description: An area with dense vegetation (low visibility) which reduces running to about 60-80% of normal speed.

name: Vegetation: slow running, good visibility
description: An area of good visibility and reduced runnability, due to, for instance, undergrowth (brambles, heather, low bushes, cut branches). Running speed is reduced to about 60-80% of normal speed.

name: Vegetation: walk
description: An area with dense trees or thickets (low visibility) which reduce running to about 20-60% of normal speed.

name: Vegetation: walk, good visibility
description: An area of good visibility that is difficult to run through, due to, for instance, undergrowth (brambles, heather, low bushes, cut branches). Running speed is reduced to about 20-60% of normal speed.

name: Vegetation: fight
description: An area of dense vegetation (trees or undergrowth) which is barely passable. Running reduced to less than about 20% of normal speed.

name: Cultivated land
description: Cultivated land, normally used for growing crops. Runnability may vary according to the type of crops grown and the time of year.

name: Orchard
description: Land planted with trees or bushes, normally in a regular pattern. The dot lines may be orientated to show the direction of planting.

name: Vineyard or similar
description: A vineyard or similar cultivated land containing dense rows of plants offering good or normal runnability in the direction of planting. The lines are orientated to show the direction of planting.

name: Distinct cultivation boundary
description: A boundary of cultivated land vegetation (symbols 401, 412, 413, 414) or a boundary between areas of cultivated land when not shown with other symbols (fence, wall, path, etc.).

name: Distinct vegetation boundary
description: A vegetation boundary within the forest, or a distinct forest edge.

name: Prominent large tree
description: Prominent large tree.

name: Prominent bush or tree
description: Prominent bush or tree.

name: Prominent vegetation feature
description: Prominent vegetation feature.

name: Paved area
description: An area with a firm surface such as asphalt, hard gravel, tiles, concrete or the like.

name: Wide road
description: Wide road. Drawn to scale.

name: Road
description: A maintained road suitable for motor vehicles in all weather. Width less than 5 m.

name: Vehicle track
description: A track or poorly maintained road suitable for vehicles only when travelling slowly.

name: Footpath
description: An easily runnable path, bicycle track or old vehicle track.

name: Small footpath
description: A runnable small path or (temporary) forest extraction track which can be followed at competition speed.

name: Less distinct small footpath
description: A runnable less distinct / visible small path or forestry extraction track.

name: Narrow ride or linear trace
description: A forest ride or a prominent trace through the terrain which does not have a distinct runnable path along it. Runnability is shown using a slightly thicker line of yellow, green or white as background.

name: Railway
description: A railway or other kind of railed track.

name: Power line, cableway or skilift
description: Power line, cableway or skilift. The bars show the exact location of the pylons.

name: Major power line
description: Major power lines should be drawn with a double line. The gap between the lines may indicate the extent of the power line.

name: Bridge / tunnel
description: Bridges and tunnels are represented using the same basic symbols. If it is not possible to get through a tunnel (or under a bridge), it shall be omitted.

name: Wall
description: A significant wall of stone, concrete, wood or other materials.

name: Retained wall
description: A significant wall of stone, concrete, wood or other materials which is seen only from one side. Half dot points to the lower level.

name: Ruined wall
description: A ruined or less distinct wall.

name: Impassable wall
description: An impassable or uncrossable wall, normally more than 1.5 m high.

name: Fence
description: If the fence forms an enclosed area, tags are placed inside.

name: Ruined fence
description: A ruined or less distinct fence. If the fence forms an enclosed area, tags are placed inside.

name: Impassable fence
description: An impassable or uncrossable fence, normally more than 1.5 m high. If the fence forms an enclosed area, tags are placed inside.

name: Crossing point
description: A way through or over a wall, fence or other linear feature, including a gate or stile.

name: Area that shall not be entered
description: An out-of-bounds area is a feature such as a private house, a garden, a factory or another industrial area.

name: Building
description: Building. Shown with its ground plan so far as the scale permits.

name: Canopy
description: An accessible and runnable area with roof.

name: Ruin
description: A ruined building. The ground plan of a ruin is shown to scale, down to the minimum size.

name: High tower
description: A high tower or large pylon. If it is in a forest, it must be visible above the level of the surrounding forest.

name: Small tower
description: An obvious small tower, platform or seat.

name: Cairn
description: A prominent cairn, memorial stone, boundary stone or trigonometric point.

name: Fodder rack
description: A fodder rack, which is free standing or attached to a tree.

name: Prominent line feature
description: A prominent man-made line feature. For example, a low pipeline (gas, water, oil, heat, etc.) or a bobsleigh / skeleton track that is clearly visible.

name: Prominent uncrossable line feature
description: An uncrossable man-made line feature. For example, a high pipeline (gas, water, oil, heat, etc.) or a bobsleigh / skeleton track.

name: Prominent man-made feature (o)
description: Prominent man-made feature (O) The definition of the symbol must be given on the map.

name: Prominent man-made feature (x)
description: Prominent man-made feature (X) The definition of the symbol must be given on the map.

name: Stairway
description: A distinct stairway through the terrain which helps to climb very steep slopes or to cross over impassable objects.

name: Magnetic north line
description: Lines placed on the map pointing to magnetic north, parallel to the sides of the paper.

name: Registration mark
description: Used for printing courses on already printed maps.

name: Spot height
description: Used for the rough assessment of height differences.

name: Start
description: The place where the orienteering starts.

name: Map issue point
description: If there is a marked route to the start point, the map issue point is marked using this symbol.

name: Control point
description: Location of the control point.

name: Control number
description: Number of the control point.

name: Course line
description: Where controls are to be visited in order, the sequence is shown using straight lines from each control to the next one.

name: Finish
description: The end of the course.

name: Marked route
description: A marked route that is a part of the course. It is mandatory to follow the marked route.

name: Out-of-bounds boundary
description: A boundary which it is not permitted to cross.

name: Out-of-bounds area
description: An out-of-bounds area shall not be entered.

name: Crossing point
description: A crossing point, for instance through or over a wall or fence, across a road or railway, through a tunnel or out-of-bounds area, or over an uncrossable boundary.

name: Out-of-bounds route
description: Competitors are allowed to cross directly over a forbidden route, but it is forbidden to go along it.

name: First aid post
description: The location of a first aid post.

name: Refreshment point
description: The location of a refreshment point which is not at a control.
